{"cursor":"34909","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Geological period |image=Blakey 300moll.jpg |o2=32.5 |co2=800 |temp=14 |sea\nlevel = Falling from 120m to present day level throughout Mississippian, then\nrising steadily to about 80m at end of period }}\n\nThe 'Carboniferous' is a geologic period and system that extends from the end of\nthe Devonian Period, about 359.2 million years ago, to the beginning of the\nPermian Period, about 299.0 Â± 0.8 Ma . The name Carboniferous means \"coal-\nbearing\" and derives from the Latin words carbo (coal) and ferre (to carry), and\nwas coined by geologists William Conybeare and William Phillips in\n1822. Rev. W. D. Conybeare and William Phillips, Outlines of the Geology of\nEngland and Wales â¦ , Part I, (London, England: William Phillips, 1822). On page\n323, Conybeare titles the chapter\n[http://books.google.com/books?id=ZcMQAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA323#v=onepage&q&f=false\n\"Book III. Medial or Carboniferous Order.\"] Based on a study of the\nBritish rock succession, it was the first of the modern 'system' names to be\nemployed, and reflects the fact that many coal beds were formed globally during\nthis time. Cossey, P.J. et al (2004) British Lower Carboniferous\nStratigraphy, Geological Conservation Review Series, no 29, JNCC, Peterborough\n(p3) The Carboniferous is often treated in North America as two geological\nperiods, the earlier Mississippian and the later Pennsylvanian.\n\nTerrestrial life was well established by the Carboniferous period. Amphibians\nwere the dominant land vertebrates, of which one branch would eventually evolve\ninto reptiles, the first fully terrestrial vertebrates. Arthropods were also\nvery common, and many (such as [[Meganeura]]), were much larger than those of\ntoday. Vast swaths of forest covered the land, which would eventually be laid\ndown and become the coal beds characteristic of the Carboniferous system. A\nminor marine and terrestrial extinction event occurred in the middle of the\nperiod, caused by a change in climate. The latter half of the\nperiod experienced glaciations, low sea level, and mountain building as the\ncontinents collided to form Pangaea.\n","linknr":950,"url":"Carboniferous","recorded":1362510574,"links":98,"instances":["continent","stratigraphy","stratigraphy","ecology","continent","physiology","geologist","continent","biology","phylogenetics","geologist","botany","biology"],"pdf":["http://www.stratigraphy.org/bak/precambrian/Gradstein_Ogg_2004.pdf","http://www.stratigraphy.org/ics%20chart/ChronostratChart2012.pdf"],"categories":["Carboniferous|","Article Feedback 5 Additional Articles"],"headings":["Subdivisions","Paleogeography","Climate","Rocks and coal","Life","Extinction events","See also","References","Further reading","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/87/Blakey_300moll.jpg/240px-Blakey_300moll.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/0/00/US_pennsylvanian_general.jpg/270px-US_pennsylvanian_general.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/MississippianMarbleUT.JPG/220px-MississippianMarbleUT.JPG","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8e/Meyers_b15_s0272b.jpg/250px-Meyers_b15_s0272b.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/08/Lycopsid_joggins_mcr1.JPG/120px-Lycopsid_joggins_mcr1.JPG","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d9/Lycopsid_mcr2.jpg/120px-Lycopsid_mcr2.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/Aviculopecten_subcardiformis01.JPG/120px-Aviculopecten_subcardiformis01.JPG","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b6/LoganFauna011312.jpg/120px-LoganFauna011312.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5f/Syringothyris01.JPG/120px-Syringot